{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11940"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11940"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0.62,0.03,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4536"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63558"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1711"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26791"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents with fever, jaundice, and loss of appetite for the past several weeks. She denies exposure to anyone with hepatitis. She denies any risk factors for viral hepatitis. Laboratory tests include AST 720 U/L (10-40), ALT 1,250 U/L (5-40), ALP 82 U/L (35-110), total bilirubin 133 umol/L (4-20), direct bilirubin 89 umol/L (\u0026lt;7), total protein 85 g/L (64-83), albumin 32 g/L (36-47). HBsAg, anti-HCV, and IgM anti-HAV are all negative; HBcAb and HBsAb are positive, but IgM anti-HBc is negative. Ceruloplasmin is 0.77 g/L (0.24-0.60), and the antinuclear antibody is positive at 1:1,280.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute alcoholic hepatitis","Acute viral hepatitis","Autoimmune hepatitis","Cirrhosis","Wilson disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E (AIH) most commonly presents as a chronic disorder, but in about 25% of cases has an acute presentation. The spectrum of clinical presentation of AIH ranges from an asymptomatic elevation of serum liver enzymes to fulminant hepatitis. The most common clinical presentation is characterised by a slow disease onset and progression with non-specific complaints such as fatigue and malaise, which explains why AIH is in advanced stages of fibrosis at the time of diagnosis in around a third of patients. The low albumin with markedly increased globulins and positive antinuclear antibody in high titre all point to this diagnosis. HBsAg negative, HBcAb and HBsAb positivity indicate previous exposure to the virus but are not consistent with acute viral hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autoimmune hepatitis is characterised by liver transaminase elevation in the presence of autoantibodies, elevated gamma globulin levels, interface hepatitis on histology, and a great response to corticosteroids.","A positive antinuclear antibody test in high titre can be indicative of autoimmune hepatitis.","Autoimmune hepatitis can present acutely, mimicking other forms of hepatitis, but is distinguished by specific serological markers."],"references":["Washington MK. Autoimmune liver disease: overlap and outliers. Mod Pathol. 2007 Feb;20 Suppl 1:S15-30. doi: 10.1038/modpathol.3800684. PMID: 17486048. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17486048/","Muratori L, Lohse AW, Lenzi M. Diagnosis and management of autoimmune hepatitis. BMJ. 2023 Feb 6;380:e070201. doi: 10.1136/bmj-2022-070201. Erratum in: BMJ. 2023 Feb 10;380:p330. doi: 10.1136/bmj.p330. PMID: 36746473. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36746473/","Tanaka A. Autoimmune Hepatitis: 2019 Update. Gut Liver. 2020 Jul 15;14(4):430-438. doi: 10.5009/gnl19261. PMID: 32301319; PMCID: PMC7366136. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32301319/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63558"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11940"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63558"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:15:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:16:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4536"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64",